{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}} {{Infobox person | image = Stein Erik Hagen, Chairman of the board.jpg | image_size = | name = Stein Erik Hagen | caption = Stein Erik Hagen | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1956|7|22|df=y}} | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | death_cause = | restingplace = | nationality = Norwegian | religion = | ethnicity = | residence = [[Oslo]], Norway | education = | alma mater = [[BI Norwegian Business School]] | occupation = Chairman, [[Orkla Group|Orkla]] | salary = | networth = [[United States dollar|$]]4.19 billion (June 2017)<ref name=Forbes>{{cite web|title=Stein Erik Hagen|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/stein-erik-hagen/|website=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=15 June 2017}}</ref> | spouse = | parents = | children = 4 | relatives = | website = }}
'''Stein Erik Hagen''' (born 22 July 1956) is a Norwegian businessman. He is chairman of [[Orkla Group|Orkla]], where he is a major shareholder, and holds large stakes in [[Steen & Strøm]], [[Jernia]] and [[Komplett]] through his family company [[Canica]]. According to the news magazine ''[[Kapital (magazine)|Kapital]]'', Hagen is worth [[Norwegian krone|NOK]] 24 billion, making him the second richest person in Norway.
==Biography== Hagen is educated at ''Kjøpmannsinsituttet'' (now part of the [[BI Norwegian Business School]]). He founded the [[RIMI]] discount store chain along with his father in the 1970s, and retained ownership until the 2000s, when he sold to Swedish [[ICA AB|ICA]] and [[Ahold]]. Most of the money was ploughed into Orkla. Hagen reportedly owns one of the biggest sailboats in Europe and used to own his own island in the Caribbean.{{cn|date=October 2015}}
He provided financial support to the [[Liberal Party of Norway|Liberal Party]] in the [[Norwegian parliamentary election, 2005|2005 Norwegian election]] and to the [[Liberal Party (Norway)|Liberal Party]], [[Christian Democratic Party (Norway)|Christian Democratic Party]], [[Conservative Party of Norway|Conservative Party]] and [[Progress Party (Norway)|Progress Party]] in 2006.{{fact|date=December 2012}}
== Private life == Stein Erik Hagen has three children from his first marriage, and a son from a later relationship.<ref>Ellen Limstrand: [http://www.kjendis.no/2012/08/20/kjendis/stein_erik_hagen/mille-marie_treschow/23044559/ Kjendisekteskap ryker oftere] ''[[Verdens Gang]]'', 8 August 2003</ref> In 2004 he married [[Mille-Marie Treschow]], the couple announced in 2012 that they were separating.<ref>Ida Grieg Riisnæs and Bente Bjørndal: [http://www.dn.no/forsiden/borsMarked/article2455409.ece Tar ut separasjon] ''[[Dagens Næringsliv]]'', 8 August 2012</ref>
In October 2015, Hagen [[Coming out|came out]] on the Norwegian-Swedish [[talk show]] ''[[Skavlan]]''. Later the same day he added that he was bisexual, and that his ex-wives and family have known about his sexuality for many years.<ref>{{cite news |last=Haugan |first=Bjørn |date=2 October 2015 |title=Hagen sier ekskonene visste at han var bifil |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/homofili-i-idretten/hagen-sier-ekskonene-visste-at-han-var-bifil/a/23535488/ |newspaper=Verdens Gang |location= |access-date=2 October 2015 |language=Norwegian}}</ref>
